uellywig.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Ellywig</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 604<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(6/19/02 8:20:37 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2163.topic&index=21>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: stupid decisions</span><hr size=1> You can find roleplay justification for almost anything, actually. Kill-stealing. Scamming. Rampant profanity. Player harassment. Those are some of the more disruptive things that I have actually *seen* people try to defend with roleplay reasons... so the fact that something <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> can</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> be given a roleplay reason doesn't mean it should. (No, not saying twinking is equivalent to scamming... reread sentence if you think it says that.)<br>
<br>
Which is why roleplay can't be the end-all, defining virtue. It has to be balanced against game mechanics and basic player fairness and campaign context and all that stuff. And against the overall effect that [insert action here] has on the game long-term. Some perfectly decent roleplay things wind up falling by the wayside to accomodate those other priorities.<br>
<br>
There are viable roleplay reasons why folks should be able to start level 60 EQ characters, too. Doesn't mean it would be good for the game, or for Verant's bottom line.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Ellywig</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
Not saying where the balance on &quot;twinking&quot; should be... <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/uteapray.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Teapray</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 7<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(6/20/02 3:20:59 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2163.topic&index=22>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: If FV was role play enforced</span><hr size=1> As many have said, it would be hard to define what &quot;role-playing&quot; is.  <br>
 <br>
     A short while after starting my high-elf cleric, and traveling to Qeynos for...well, honestly, I forget for what, but I was there, some human male approaches her as she stood in front of the soul binder.  He proceeded to crudely flirt with her, making not so clever sexual innuduoes.  Things like &quot;You're very appetizing... I'd love a cup of Tea! (my character's name is Teapray).&quot;   I played the haughty high-elf well, and answered in character the way one would expect a lady to.  I was fairly civil though..I think the worst thing I told him is that  &quot;I don't need compliments from the likes of you&quot;.  He got mad then, and informed me that this was role-playing server.  Didn't I know how to roleplay?   Apparently, he expected any female he ran across to roleplay as an air-headed slut.  I was getting tells from others nearby telling me what an idiot he was, and to stand my ground.  By their criteria, I was role-playing just fine.<br>
   Also, my character is in love with an ogre warrior, who is in real life played by my husband.  I am in love with my husband.  I have a strong back-story on why we are together.  Good role-playing?  Several people who just meet us seem to think not, till they talk to us, and then decide we are fine role-players.  /shrug.<br>
<br>
