--------------------------<br>
<br>
The rules on the DAOC servers are simple: No inappropriate names and no OOC speech in public.<br>
<br>
For the most part, both rules work and they provide a much more pleasant environment.<br>
<br>
However, they are so popular with gamers, that people just seeking escape from d00diespeak flooded the RP servers. That's the biggest problem because it did dilute the amount of real roleplaying.<br>
<br>
DAOC also has very small server populations because the servers are split into 3 realms and it makes it very hard to get away from people, which degrades the ability to get roleplaying going. I've been on raids where a full third of everyone on the server was taking part. I suspect the rules would work far far better in a PVE game like EQ where you don't need to deal with everyone.<br>
<br>
It's far far from perfect, but for roleplayers it's a heck of a lot easier to roleplay when you don't have idiot names running around babbling about nascar or whatever.<br>
<br>
As far as &quot;who's roleplaying.&quot; This is really a red herring. It just never comes up. There were some people who played it very close to real medieval and others who were pretty free form with it. But it just never became an issue--people lived and let live. Roleplayers are nice people for the most part and are so grateful to have any bone thrown to them that they try to make it work. Not to mention that there are enough non-roleplayers to worry about. <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/unumtinae.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Numtinae</A> at: 6/20/02 2:15:22 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/uteapray.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Teapray</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 9<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(6/20/02 11:27:23 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2163.topic&index=27>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: If FV was role play enforced</span><hr size=1> There's no need to put &quot;love&quot; in quotion marks, Silenae.  We really are in love, and our characters are too.   And we do accept that some may not want to group with us.  In fact, it kinda plays into our backstory.  Teapray, while  rebellious to her family, really does love and miss them, and would be delighted if her father would accept her new love, and let her go back home to the wealth of her family.  She tries hard to get other elves to accept Lenny, in hopes that they words of his worth might get back to her father and sway his judgement.  But she knows it is going to be an up-hill battle.  If everyone accepted us, it would kinda kill that aspect of the roleplaying.  It's more fun when others play along, by telling us what disgraces we are.<br>
For what it's worth, I much rather be around the dark elf I met in the Paladul Caverns, who kept snarling at me meanly and telling me how much he would enjoy the sight of Innoruuk feasting on my entrails, then the many, many people who have responded to my drive-by buffs with &quot;thx&quot; or use &quot;o i c&quot;  when I answered a question for  them.<br>
<br>
